Federal authorities put up a temporary "non-scalable" fence at the White House on Monday in efforts to increase security on Election Day.
A widely shared image on Facebook of an aerial view of the White House and a massive wall claims to show that recently installed protection.

"Doesn’t get any crazier than this! Look at this monstrosity the Stable Genius has built in the middle of our nation's capitol, in *our White House...the People's House," reads a Facebook post accompanied by the image.
The same photo and caption has since been reposted by several users on Facebook, to whom USA TODAY reached out for comment.
The claim was also shared by the Other 98%, however, the page has since updated its post after being fact-checked by another news organization.

A Google reverse image search reveals that the image has been altered and is from over a decade ago.
The image was taken on Sept. 17, 2009, by photographer Carol M. Highsmith, according to Getty Images. There is no wall visible in the photo.
The National Park Service told the Associated Press that the Facebook image does not resemble actual fencing on the White House Complex.

Federal authorities were seen putting up additional fencing around the perimeter of the White House on Monday, USA TODAY reported.
The barriers are similar to the ones installed in Washington during Black Lives Matter protests over the summer following the death of George Floyd.
The fence goes down 15th Street to Constitution Avenue and over to 17th Street, then runs up to H Street and across by Lafayette Park and back down 15th Street, according to CNN.

Photos of the temporary fence in front of the White House reveal that it does not look similar to the one in the Facebook image. Other photos show that the current fencing is covered in protest signs.

This image does not show a massive wall in front of the White House. It is fabricated from a 2009 image and the National Park Service has confirmed that the photo does not resemble actual fencing at the White House. While federal authorities did put up fencing around the White House, it is not similar to the one in the image, therefore we rate this claim as FALSE.
